<plot>It was October 1929 when Black Thursday launched the world into the darkest time in modern economic history. Earlier that year, Ernest Hemingway wrote in A Farewell To Arms: "The world breaks everyone and afterward many are strong in the broken places." "When the World Breaks" is about creativity and survival in desperate times, specifically during the Great Depression of the 1930s, with striking parallels to our current Great Recession. Our story begins with a simple premise: Extreme times are also times of heightened creativity and innovation - when necessity truly does become the mother of invention. So perhaps in looking back at Depression-era life, art, cinema, literature, music, architecture, entertainment, culture, politics... we can discover new ways to see ourselves today. Because when the world breaks, revolutions erupt and people wake up - to become stronger in the broken places - as urgently now as 80 years ago.</plot><url>http://localhost:8983/solr/movie.html?653632</url></doc>
